WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960
 - Hello, and welcome to Python Objects.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:04.840
 I'm Charles Severance and we're well on our way

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:08.720
 to getting through all this material in the Python.

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:10.880
 So this lecture is in a weird place.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:13.080
 I even debated where to put it in the book.

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:16.760
 I don't really wanna teach you how to write

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:18.360
 a lot of object-oriented programming,

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:20.560
 but we're gonna start using objects

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:23.400
 and I wanna be able to use the terminology.

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:27.040
 And so as much as anything, this lecture is about terminology

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:30.240
 and understanding the words, things like methods

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:33.920
 and method signatures and variables and inheritance.

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:36.320
 And so think of this as a terminology lecture

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:39.840
 rather than a learn how to program or learn how to use this.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.720
 It's not something you're gonna figure out right away

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:45.120
 and there'll come a time when you as a programmer

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:47.080
 really wanna start using object-oriented programming.

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:49.880
 It's really a powerful and wonderful technique,

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:53.240
 but I think it's too early as a beginning programmer

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:55.440
 to really say, oh, let's write a bunch of objects.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:01:00.440
 So just relax and enjoy and learn this material

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:03.740
 and think of it as sort of a theoretical thing

00:01:03.740 --> 00:01:06.200
 rather than a how to program thing.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:11.880
 And so part of this is we're gonna start reading

00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:16.240
 data structures and I mean data on how to use

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:18.080
 all these libraries, et cetera.

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:19.960
 And we're gonna see the word objects, right?

00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:21.800
 And then we're gonna start hearing them.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.080
 And I want you to be able to read the Python documentation

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:26.080
 so that you understand what's going on.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:29.600
 And so the word objects should make sense to you

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:31.000
 even though you're not gonna write

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:32.440
 a lot of object-oriented programming.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:35.680
 And so page upon page upon page,

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:37.740
 database stuff which we're gonna talk about soon

00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:40.240
 is uses objects all over the place.

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:43.740
 And the beautiful soup talks about uses objects.

00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:47.000
 We've kind of been using them and I've been waving my hands

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.240
 and I use the word method without defining it,

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:53.680
 but now it's really time to define it and go to it.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:58.680
 So I wanna review from the very beginning

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:00.560
 what we think of as a program.

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:03.560
 So the classic program, my favorite little minimum program

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.920
 is our little elevator floor converter

00:02:06.920 --> 00:02:09.240
 which converts from European elevator floors

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:11.120
 to United States elevator floors.

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:15.400
 And the key to this is that it's input processing and output

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:18.680
 and this is a good way to model any program.

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.800
 And in that process we've got variables

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:25.440
 and we've got logic, we've got algorithms,

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:27.960
 we've got loops that we write, we've got all kinds of things

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:32.620
 and we construct a series of steps to achieve some goal.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:36.920
 In object-oriented, and frankly you've been using

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:41.920
 object-oriented all along, the program has lots of objects

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:43.860
 and we're sort of putting stuff into these objects,

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:45.240
 taking stuff out of one object

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:46.760
 and putting it into another object.

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:48.640
 And you've actually been doing this all along

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:50.940
 as soon as you're looking at dictionaries and lists,

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:52.860
 you're doing objects.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:56.960
 And so an object is quite a little thing,

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.020
 it's sort of its own little space inside of a program

00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:02.440
 that contains code and data.

00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:05.800
 And so we're working together,

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:07.480
 all these objects are now working together.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:09.760
 It's a bit of self-contained code and data

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:13.980
 and it is one way to take a very complex problem

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:17.600
 and make it easier by breaking into separate things

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:19.840
 that can be engineered and developed separately.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:21.960
 So you've been using string objects

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:24.180
 or maybe you'd use beautiful soup or something.

00:03:24.180 --> 00:03:25.720
 These are powerful capabilities

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.880
 and if you had to look at all of them,

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:29.960
 it's just hey, here's a thing, use this object,

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:31.200
 it'll do these things for you

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:33.420
 and there's lots of details inside of it,

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:35.600
 just don't look at it, don't worry about it.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:38.260
 And so there's boundaries, the things that you can use,

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:39.640
 things that you can look at

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:41.680
 and things that really you don't bother looking at,

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:45.660
 you go read the documentation and use it and away it goes.

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:47.120
 But then someone had to write that

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:48.860
 and so they built an object.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:50.560
 So what we're gonna do is look a little bit

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:51.940
 under the covers of what it takes

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:54.440
 to build some of these objects.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:59.720
 And so if we think of this program

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:02.120
 that originally just sort of did processing,

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:05.320
 we can think of it as having some kind of an input, right,

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:06.860
 coming into our program.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:09.260
 And we have a string object, a dictionary object,

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:11.820
 maybe eventually some objects like a database object

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:13.980
 or an object that we eventually define.

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:16.160
 And you can think of us, we're receiving data,

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:18.380
 it comes in an object which is a string object

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:21.120
 where you start putting the strings in dictionaries

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.420
 and do whatever, we pull out a list of them.

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:27.020
 And so you can think of data as moving between these objects.

00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:30.660
 And like I say, even strings, in the first week,

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:33.660
 first lecture, first week, first everything,

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:38.540
 we were using objects and we've been using them all along.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:41.460
 And so you can think of every string and every dictionary

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:44.240
 as a little program all by itself

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:48.220
 that has a bit of code and a bit of data.

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:50.340
 And so a string has the data which includes

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:51.900
 all the characters that make up the string,

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:54.500
 but then there is a method called upper

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:57.780
 that does uppercase or rstrip that strips off the right,

00:04:57.780 --> 00:04:59.480
 a white space from the right.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.580
 And so it's like they're almost little programs

00:05:01.580 --> 00:05:03.940
 that have inputs and outputs themselves

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:05.060
 and we can make lots of them.

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:07.060
 And there's lots of cooperating objects

00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:09.620
 that make up an application.

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:13.860
 And one of the nice things about the object-oriented pattern

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:17.060
 is that they form boundaries.

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:19.780
 And within the boundary, if you're inside the object,

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.700
 you can say, look, I'm gonna build you a string object

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:25.300
 or a database object or a beautiful soup object.

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:26.660
 And I'm gonna build this capability

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:29.260
 and I'm gonna give it to you in the form of an interface.

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:31.340
 And I'm not really gonna care how you use it.

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:34.220
 And so we have this sort of visibility wall

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:37.300
 where I'm gonna make an object and I'm gonna let you use it

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:39.140
 and the maker of the object doesn't necessarily

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:41.260
 have to know every single thing

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.300
 about the use of that object.

00:05:43.300 --> 00:05:45.700
 But so just like inside the object,

00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:47.140
 they don't have to worry about what you're doing

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:48.740
 with the object outside of it,

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:49.840
 when you're outside the object,

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.100
 you don't have to worry about what's going on inside of it.

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:55.460
 We, as the user of the object, we talk to its interface

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:57.420
 and we get things from it and give things to it

00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:59.740
 and use functionality within that object.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:01.460
 But we don't have to look inside of this.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:04.140
 We can just say, oh, it's a nice little magical thing.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:06.200
 We read the documentation, we read a webpage,

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:08.880
 and it told us to do this, this, and this, and away you go.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.260
 And so it is sort of this isolation boundary

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:15.020
 that works both for the programmer

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:17.260
 who's writing the object and the programmer

00:06:17.260 --> 00:06:19.120
 who's using the object.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:21.780
 And so it's a very nice pattern.

00:06:21.780 --> 00:06:25.660
 And so you'll see how we're gonna build code

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:26.700
 and we're gonna group it together

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:27.860
 and then we're gonna be using it

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:30.360
 sort of as a big blob of stuff.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:34.800
 So some definitions in this space,

00:06:34.800 --> 00:06:37.800
 words that I want you to understand.

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:41.820
 When we're gonna create one of these things,

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:44.340
 one of these objects, instances,

00:06:44.340 --> 00:06:47.280
 that has some data in it and some code in it,

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:49.940
 we have to be able to define the shape of this object.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:52.100
 What code will each object have in it

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:54.700
 and what data will each object have in it?

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:56.720
 And that's called a class.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:58.660
 The key to a class, and this little picture

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:01.540
 that I've got up here in all these slides, is a key.

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:02.920
 The class is a template.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:04.100
 It's not the thing itself.

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:05.340
 So it's a cookie cutter.

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:08.120
 It knows a lot about how cookies are made.

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:10.720
 And if you have cookie dough and you hit the thing,

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:12.700
 then you make as many cookies as you want.

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:15.440
 And so this nice little cookie picture

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:19.940
 is a great, you know, mental model of how it works.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:22.200
 The class, the class, oops.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:28.680
 The class is the template.

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:32.600
 And then the object are all of the cookies

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:34.180
 that are made from that template.

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:36.500
 But the template defines the shape

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:37.620
 and the nature of the class.

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:41.780
 So the code that we write is of each of the objects.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:44.360
 The code we write is the class code.

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:46.700
 And then later we say, oh, let's take that template

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.940
 and make ourselves an object or an instance.

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:52.980
 Now, as we're defining a class,

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.620
 we have two basic things that we put in the class.

00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:58.020
 And there's a couple of different terminologies for this.

00:07:58.020 --> 00:07:59.780
 One is method, which is code.

00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:02.080
 It's like a function that lives inside of a class.

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:04.740
 Not a function that lives inside your program,

00:08:04.740 --> 00:08:06.280
 but one that lives inside of a class.

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:08.020
 And so this is a scoping thing.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:10.760
 A method is really just a function.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:13.200
 But it's lived, it lives inside the class.

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:15.620
 And then fields or attributes are data items

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:16.460
 that are in the class.

00:08:16.460 --> 00:08:19.160
 And so they're variables that are defined in the class.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:20.900
 You can define variables outside the class

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:21.820
 that you use in your program.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:23.180
 You've been doing that all along.

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:25.180
 But if you're saying, I'm gonna build this capability

00:08:25.180 --> 00:08:27.920
 and it's gonna have data inside of it and code inside of it,

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:30.780
 the code is the method or message and field or attribute.

00:08:30.780 --> 00:08:33.200
 And they're just, oops.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:39.320
 There are just two different sets of terminology.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:41.020
 Method is what I'll probably use.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:42.980
 If you look in some object-oriented patterns

00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:46.620
 like Smalltalk or Apple, they often don't call

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:47.460
 these messages.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:50.620
 So you can either access a method inside of a class

00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:53.980
 or an object, or you can send a message to the object.

00:08:53.980 --> 00:08:55.700
 The same is true for field and attribute.

00:08:55.700 --> 00:08:57.660
 It's just a chunk of data that's in the object

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:01.080
 that you may or may not have the right to access.

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:05.980
 So, like I said, a class is a template.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:08.200
 It defines the characteristics of the objects

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:09.480
 that we're gonna use to make it.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:11.020
 It is the cookie cutter.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:17.660
 So, dog is sort of the exemplar.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:19.060
 Lassie is a particular dog.

00:09:19.060 --> 00:09:21.180
 And so dog has fur and dog barks

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:22.580
 and dogs do all these things.

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:24.720
 And so we know something about dogs,

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:27.140
 but it doesn't mean we have a dog, right?

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:30.100
 And the class is a more abstract concept

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:31.860
 that when it's time to get a dog,

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:34.680
 we know certain things about dogs.

00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:38.860
 Instances, or objects, are once we say,

00:09:38.860 --> 00:09:41.820
 oh, time to make a cookie from the template.

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:42.860
 Time to get a dog.

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:44.720
 We know something about dogs.

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:46.900
 That's the creation of an object.

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:49.900
 And we call them instances, instance of a class.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:53.740
 So the class doesn't exist, but we say,

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:57.400
 make me a new object using this class as its template.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:09:58.580
 Oh, and now make me another one.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:01.580
 And so we can have many, many objects from one class.

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:05.260
 So just like many cookies from one cookie cutter.

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:10.540
 Method is a bit of code that lives inside of an object.

00:10:10.540 --> 00:10:13.940
 It's like a function, but it's scoped to within the object,

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:15.240
 or within the class.

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:18.060
 Okay, so that kind of gets us started

00:10:18.060 --> 00:10:19.860
 on some of the terminology.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:21.140
 And we'll come back and we'll take a look

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:25.140
 at how we write code that's object-oriented.

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:27.560
 (jazz music)

00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:34.660
 (soft piano music)

